? The JaCoCo report measures line coverage per package and source file. If the test code package `net.sf.cglib.beans` and the source file `BeanCopier.java` cover line 31, could that lead to a source key collision? JaCoCo uses package and source file names, but do tests get excluded? I wonder if the report includes both library and test packages.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "No additional test-only change is likely to cover this remaining call site.\n\nThe remaining site is:\n\n```text\nnet.sf.cglib.beans.BeanCopier.class$(BeanCopier.java:31)\n```\n\nThis is a compiler-generated synthetic `class$` helper for the old-style `BeanCopierKey.class` class literal in `BeanCopier` static initialization:\n\n```java\nprivate static final BeanCopierKey KEY_FACTORY =\n  (BeanCopierKey)KeyFactory.create(BeanCopierKey.class);\n```\n\nThe dedicated test file already exercises the public `BeanCopier` initialization and creation paths:\n\n- `BeanCopier.create(...)`\n- `new BeanCopier.Generator()`\n- `generator.create()`\n- `copy(...)` with and without a converter\n\nThose paths naturally initialize `BeanCopier` and execute the public API that reaches the generated helper. However, JaCoCo does not expose coverage for the synthetic `class$` method/line in this artifact, so the dynamic-access coverage report continues to show line `31` as uncovered even though the runtime dynamic-access report observes the call.\n\nI did not add direct reflection or synthetic-method invocation because that would violate the task constraints and would not be an idiomatic public-API integration test.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0969d36bc46c10920169f5ad495dd081a2ad03e8ca71ca101c\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1662, "output": 3888, "cacheRead": 47104, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 52654, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp"